    summary: 'The American bald eagle, once on the brink of extinction, has rebounded to over 316,000 birds in the contiguous United States — a remarkable conservation success story fifty years in the making.',
    content: 'Once reduced to just 417 nesting pairs in the lower 48 states, the bald eagle teetered on the edge of extinction through the mid-20th century. The pesticide DDT — widely used in agriculture — caused the eagles\' eggshells to thin so severely that they cracked under the weight of incubating parents, preventing reproduction almost entirely. Hunting, habitat loss, and lead poisoning from spent ammunition compounded the crisis, and by the early 1960s the species had been eliminated from most of its historic range.\n\nThe turnaround began with the 1972 ban on DDT and accelerated with federal protections under the Endangered Species Act of 1973, which made it a federal crime to harm, harass, or kill bald eagles. Wildlife agencies established captive breeding programs, reintroduced birds into regions where they had vanished, and worked with landowners to protect critical nesting habitat along rivers and coastlines. Bald eagles were officially removed from the endangered species list in 2007, but conservation efforts continued.\n\nToday the U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service estimates that more than 316,000 bald eagles live in the contiguous United States — more than at any time since European settlement. Nesting pairs can now be found in every contiguous state, from the marshes of Florida to the forests of Maine to the deserts of Arizona. The recovery stands as one of the most inspiring proof-of-concept stories for the Endangered Species Act, demonstrating that strong legal protection and sustained scientific investment can pull a species back from the brink.',
