    summary: 'More than 1,500 Detroit residents are growing their own food through a network of urban farms on former vacant land, improving food security and rebuilding community bonds in neighborhoods hardest hit by deindustrialization.',
    content: "At the height of Detroit's post-industrial decline, the city had more than 40 square miles of vacant land — overgrown lots, demolished homes, and abandoned factories that stood as monuments to decades of economic collapse. Today, that same vacant land is being transformed into one of the most ambitious urban agriculture networks in the United States. The Detroit Black Community Food Security Network, D-Town Farm, and dozens of smaller community garden cooperatives now cultivate fresh produce across more than 1,500 individual plots in neighborhoods that have long been classified as food deserts, where the nearest grocery store can be miles away.\n\nThe farms grow everything from kale and collard greens to tomatoes, peppers, squash, and sweet corn, with produce distributed through community shares, local farmers markets, and donation programs targeting elderly and low-income residents. Young people from the community earn wages and agricultural training through summer employment programs, gaining skills in soil science, composting, irrigation, and business management. Program leaders say the gardens accomplish something that food banks alone cannot: they restore a sense of agency and self-sufficiency to communities that have historically been excluded from economic opportunity.\n\nThe success of Detroit's urban agriculture movement has attracted attention from city planners and food security researchers around the world. The city government has since passed ordinances to formalize urban farming zoning, making it easier for residents to start new plots and for established farms to expand. Participants say the transformation goes far beyond vegetables — vacant lots that once attracted illegal dumping and crime are now spaces where neighbors gather, children learn, and communities rebuild bonds that decades of disinvestment had frayed.",
