    summary: 'The American Cancer Society reports that cancer death rates have fallen 33% since 1991, with the biggest drops in lung, colorectal, breast, and melanoma cancers — representing 3.8 million lives saved.',
    content: 'A landmark report from the American Cancer Society revealed that the overall cancer death rate in the United States dropped by 33% between 1991 and 2022, representing the longest and deepest sustained decline in cancer mortality ever recorded. The reduction translates to approximately 3.8 million lives saved that would otherwise have been lost to cancer — a number that exceeds the entire population of Los Angeles. The peak in 1991 coincided with the height of the smoking epidemic, and the single biggest driver of improvement since then has been the dramatic decline in smoking rates across all age groups.\n\nBeyond smoking cessation, advances in early detection have dramatically changed outcomes for several of the most common cancers. Mammography and improved breast cancer screening protocols, colonoscopy programs that catch colorectal cancer before it spreads, and low-dose CT scanning for high-risk lung cancer patients have all contributed to finding cancers at earlier, more treatable stages. Immunotherapy — a revolutionary approach that trains the immune system to recognize and destroy cancer cells — has transformed previously terminal diagnoses of melanoma, lung cancer, and certain leukemias into manageable or even curable conditions for many patients.\n\nDespite the remarkable progress, researchers caution that gains are not equally shared. Cancer death rates remain significantly higher among Black Americans for most cancer types, and rural communities continue to lag behind urban areas in access to screening and cutting-edge treatments. The American Cancer Society is calling for expanded Medicaid coverage, investment in rural oncology centers, and community health worker programs to ensure that the progress achieved in research labs reaches every American regardless of income or zip code.',
