    content: "The California Air Resources Board has accelerated its historic mandate to replace every diesel school bus in the state with a zero-emission electric vehicle by 2035, with over 1,000 electric buses already on the road serving students from San Diego to Sacramento. The program, backed by more than $1 billion in federal funding from the EPA's Clean School Bus Program, is targeting districts in low-income communities and heavily polluted air basins first — the areas where children have historically borne the greatest health burden from diesel exhaust.\n\nThe health case for the switch is compelling. Diesel exhaust from school buses — which idle for long periods outside schools every day — has been linked to higher rates of childhood asthma, respiratory infections, and diminished lung development. Studies have found that children who ride diesel buses are exposed to up to four times more air pollution than those who travel by car. Early data from districts that have transitioned shows measurable improvements in attendance and test scores in the years following the switch, supporting the theory that cleaner air directly improves children's ability to learn.\n\nBeyond clean air, the electric buses are proving surprisingly versatile. Several school districts are enrolling their buses in vehicle-to-grid programs, using the buses' large battery packs to feed electricity back to the local grid during peak demand periods and to power school buildings during wildfire-related outages — effectively turning the fleet into a distributed energy asset. Bus drivers report that the vehicles are quieter, smoother, and require significantly less maintenance than diesel counterparts, making recruitment and retention of drivers easier in a sector that has long struggled with workforce shortages.",
