    title: 'Scotland Hits 100% Renewable Electricity Target for Entire Year',
    summary: 'Scotland generated enough wind, hydro, and solar electricity to meet its entire electricity demand from renewables for a full year — a milestone once considered impossible, achieved ahead of schedule.',
    content: "Scotland has become one of the first nations in the world to generate the equivalent of 100% of its electricity needs from renewable sources over the course of a full year — a milestone that energy experts once considered decades away. Wind energy was the workhorse of the achievement: on the windiest days, Scottish turbines generated 113% of domestic electricity demand, with surplus power exported to England and beyond via interconnector cables. Offshore wind farms in the North Sea and onshore turbines across the Highlands and Southern Uplands now form one of the densest concentrations of wind power per capita anywhere on Earth.\n\nThe achievement is the result of consistent policy investment stretching back to the 1990s, when Scotland began building its first commercial wind farms against significant public opposition. Subsequent Scottish governments of different political stripes maintained and expanded renewable energy targets, providing long-term certainty that encouraged private developers to invest billions in turbine manufacturing, grid upgrades, and battery storage infrastructure. Hydroelectric power from the Scottish Highlands provides crucial backup generation during calm periods, acting as a natural battery that can be dispatched at will.\n\nScotland's next ambition is green hydrogen — using surplus renewable electricity to split water into hydrogen and oxygen through electrolysis, producing a zero-carbon fuel that can be stored, transported, and used to power ships, heavy industry, and heating systems that are difficult to electrify directly. The country aims to become a major hydrogen exporter to Germany, the Netherlands, and other European nations that face greater challenges in generating domestic renewables. Industry analysts say Scotland is well-positioned to become one of the world's leading clean energy exporters within a decade.",
