    summary: "Portugal's national grid ran entirely on renewable electricity — wind, hydro, and solar — for six days straight, demonstrating that a modern European economy can function without fossil fuels.",
    content: "Renewable energy sources powered the entirety of Portugal for six consecutive days — 144 consecutive hours — setting a record for a European nation with a substantial industrial economy. Wind turbines generated the majority of the power during the streak, backed by hydroelectric dams in the country's river valleys and a rapidly expanding fleet of solar farms in the sunny Alentejo and Algarve regions. Rather than drawing on fossil fuel reserves during the period, Portugal actually exported surplus electricity to Spain and France, earning revenue from its clean power abundance while its neighbors remained more dependent on gas and coal.\n\nThe achievement builds on years of deliberate energy policy. Portugal began investing heavily in wind power in the early 2000s, offering feed-in tariffs that made wind development economically attractive at a time when turbine costs were still high. By the early 2010s, the country was already generating more than 70% of its electricity from renewables in good years. The addition of large-scale solar capacity and grid-scale battery storage in the following decade pushed the system toward the ability to run fossil-fuel-free for extended periods.\n\nEnergy analysts say Portugal's achievement carries a powerful message for energy policy debates happening around the world: that modern economies can run on 100% clean electricity, not just for a few minutes or hours during optimal conditions, but for days at a time. The key enabling technologies — pumped hydro storage, battery banks, smart demand management, and interconnected grids that can share power across regions — are all commercially available today. Portugal has essentially run the experiment that skeptics said couldn't be done, and the lights stayed on.",
