    id: 'eu-003',
    title: 'EU Begins Restoring 1 Million Hectares Under Landmark Nature Law',
    summary: "The European Union's Nature Restoration Law — the most ambitious rewilding legislation in history — begins restoring degraded rivers, forests, and wetlands across the continent.",
    content: "The European Union has begun implementing its landmark Nature Restoration Law — the most ambitious rewilding legislation in human history — which requires member states to restore at least 20% of the EU's degraded land and sea areas by 2030, rising to 90% by 2050. The law passed after years of political controversy, with agricultural lobbies arguing it would threaten food production and member state governments deeply divided. Its passage marks a historic shift in European environmental policy from preservation alone toward active ecological repair at continental scale.\n\nOn the ground, restoration is already underway. The law mandates the removal of barriers — weirs, dams, culverts — that have fragmented Europe's river systems and blocked the migration of salmon, trout, and other fish for generations. In Ireland, Atlantic salmon are already returning to rivers that had been commercially barren for decades after old mill weirs were removed. Drained peatlands, which release enormous amounts of stored carbon when dry, are being rewetted across Finland, Germany, and the Netherlands, simultaneously rebuilding habitat for rare birds and locking carbon back into the soil. In the Iberian Peninsula, rewilded agricultural margins are supporting recoveries of endangered pollinators that underpin the continent's food production.\n\nConservation biologists say the scale of the ambition is unprecedented in peacetime Europe. The reintroduction of apex predators — wolves, lynx, and in some regions even bison — to areas where they vanished centuries ago is already accelerating natural regeneration by changing the behavior of deer and other grazers, allowing forests to recover in ways that passive protection alone cannot achieve. The EU estimates that successful implementation will create 500,000 new green jobs and generate economic returns in ecosystem services — clean water, flood control, pollination, carbon sequestration — worth several times the cost of the restoration itself.",
