    title: "Norway's Electric Vehicles Reach 90% of New Car Sales",
    summary: "Norway became the first country in the world where electric vehicles account for nine in ten new car sales, fueled by generous government incentives and a nationwide charging infrastructure.",
    content: "Norway has shattered global records for electric vehicle adoption, with battery-electric cars now accounting for over 90% of new passenger vehicle registrations — a figure no other country has come close to achieving. In Norway's capital Oslo, the share exceeds 95%. The transition has been driven not by a single dramatic intervention but by decades of remarkably consistent policy across successive governments of different political persuasions: EVs are exempt from import duties and 25% VAT, enjoy reduced registration fees, benefit from free parking in many city centers, pay no tolls on the extensive network of Norwegian fjord-crossing tunnels and ferries, and are permitted to use bus lanes during rush hour.\n\nThe cumulative effect of these incentives meant that for much of the 2010s, an electric vehicle actually cost less to buy, operate, and maintain in Norway than an equivalent petrol car — flipping the economics of the transition entirely. Norway's cold winters and mountainous terrain, factors that skeptics long cited as barriers to EV adoption, turned out to be manageable with modern battery technology. Norwegians report that EVs perform well in sub-zero temperatures and that the country's 20,000+ public charging stations — the most per capita anywhere on Earth — have eliminated range anxiety for most drivers.\n\nThe Norwegian model is now being studied by governments around the world as a blueprint for rapid electrification. Analysts note that the country's abundant hydropower made the switch to EVs genuinely clean from a whole-system perspective, since the electricity powering Norway's cars comes almost entirely from zero-carbon sources. Norway aims to have essentially no new petrol or diesel cars sold by 2025 — a target it is already on track to meet — and is now turning its attention to electrifying its large commercial fishing fleet and domestic aviation sector.",
