    summary: "Dutch engineers opened a 100-kilometre solar bicycle highway connecting major cities, generating clean energy while providing a safe, comfortable route for the nation's millions of daily cyclists.",
    content: "The Netherlands unveiled its first solar-powered bicycle superhighway — a 100-kilometre network of dedicated cycling routes connecting major Dutch cities with photovoltaic panels integrated into overhead canopies and in some sections embedded into the path surface itself. The route is designed to serve both daily commuters and leisure cyclists, with wide, smooth lanes separated from motor traffic and lighting powered entirely by the solar panels above. Sensors embedded in the path detect ice or frost and activate low-energy heating elements to keep the surface clear in winter — a critical feature for year-round cycling in the Dutch climate.\n\nThe energy generated by the canopy panels is fed back to the local electricity grid, effectively making the cycling infrastructure a power plant. Engineers estimate the 100-kilometre route generates enough clean electricity annually to power several hundred households. The embedded-panel sections, developed by a Dutch startup called SolaRoad, use tempered glass over monocrystalline solar cells that are designed to withstand the impact of bicycle tires and remain slip-resistant in wet conditions — technical challenges that took nearly a decade of research and iteration to solve.\n\nThe Netherlands already has the densest cycling infrastructure of any country in the world, with more than 35,000 kilometres of dedicated bike paths and over 17 million bicycles — more than one per person. The solar highway builds on that foundation, asking whether transport infrastructure can do double duty as clean energy generation. Dutch urban planners say the project points toward a future where every road, roof, and public surface is also an energy asset. International delegations from Germany, Denmark, Japan, and the United States have visited to study the model, and several cities are exploring similar projects.",
