    title: 'France Bans Short-Haul Domestic Flights to Boost Train Travel',
    summary: 'France enacted a law eliminating short domestic flights on routes served by train journeys of under 2.5 hours, cutting aviation emissions and nudging millions of travellers toward lower-carbon rail.',
    content: "France made history by becoming one of the first countries in the world to formally ban short-haul domestic flights on routes where high-speed train alternatives are available with journey times under two and a half hours. Routes between Paris Orly and the cities of Bordeaux, Lyon, and Nantes were the first to be eliminated, with the flights replaced by TGV high-speed rail connections that already carried the vast majority of travelers on those corridors. The law passed after years of debate and lobbying from airline groups, and represents a direct application of European climate policy to a specific, practical behavior change.\n\nThe aviation industry argued that the ban was largely symbolic — the affected flights carried fewer than 500,000 passengers per year, a fraction of total French air travel — but environmental campaigners countered that the precedent matters enormously. A short-haul flight generates roughly 50 times more CO2 per passenger than an equivalent rail journey on France's electricity-powered TGV network, and the law creates a legal template that could be extended to longer routes or adopted by other countries. Spain, Germany, and Austria have since announced similar measures or expansions of their high-speed rail networks with explicit goals of replacing domestic aviation.\n\nBeyond the direct emissions reduction, the law is reshaping investment decisions. Air France has redirected resources from abandoned domestic routes into its long-haul transatlantic network, and the French government announced additional investment in high-speed rail infrastructure to reduce travel times on routes that could eventually qualify for similar bans. Transport researchers say France's policy demonstrates that decarbonizing travel does not require sacrifice — when trains are fast, comfortable, and city-center to city-center, most travelers prefer them over the hassle of airports.",
    sourceUrl: 'https://www.cnbc.com/2023/05/24/france-bans-domestic-short-haul-flights.html',
    sourceName: 'CNBC',
