    id: 'af-001',
    title: 'Mountain Gorilla Population Climbs to Over 1,000 for First Time',
    summary: 'Conservation efforts in Rwanda, Uganda, and the Democratic Republic of Congo have pushed the mountain gorilla population above 1,000 individuals — a species once feared extinct by 2000.',
    content: "The mountain gorilla, once one of the world's most critically endangered animals, has passed the landmark of 1,000 individuals — a number that conservationists in the 1980s feared the species would never again reach. At its lowest point, the population had fallen to fewer than 250 individuals, fragmented across a shrinking mountain forest on the borders of Rwanda, Uganda, and the Democratic Republic of Congo, threatened by habitat loss, civil war, poaching, and disease. The prospect of extinction felt very real to the scientists who dedicated their careers to the species.\n\nThe recovery is one of the most technically complex conservation achievements of the 21st century. Anti-poaching patrols in Virunga and Bwindi national parks operate around the clock, with rangers risking their lives daily in regions that remain politically unstable. A dedicated mountain gorilla veterinary program provides medical care for injured or ill individuals — removing snares from limbs, treating respiratory infections, intervening when infants are orphaned — at a level of individual attention rarely applied to wild animals. Community conservation programs deliberately share eco-tourism revenues with the villages that border the parks, giving local families a direct financial stake in keeping the gorillas alive and the parks intact.\n\nThe tourism economics are substantial: a single permit to spend one hour with a gorilla family costs $1,500 in Rwanda, and the national parks generate tens of millions of dollars annually for local economies. This has transformed the relationship between gorillas and neighboring communities from competition over land and resources into a partnership with shared interests. Researchers have also documented that the gorilla population is increasingly healthy at the genetic level, with diversity sufficient to sustain long-term recovery. The mountain gorilla has become the gold standard for what targeted, well-funded, community-integrated conservation can achieve.",
