    id: 'as-002',
    title: "Japan's Centenarian Population Surpasses 90,000 for the First Time",
    summary: "Japan's number of people aged 100 or older surpassed 90,000, with researchers studying the country's longevity communities for insights into the diet, social connection, and lifestyle habits that promote extreme longevity.",
    content: "Japan's government announced that the number of people aged 100 or older living in the country has surpassed 90,000 for the first time — a figure that would have seemed extraordinary just a generation ago and that makes Japan home to more centenarians per capita than any other large nation. The announcement, made annually on Respect for the Aged Day, has become something of a national celebration, with local governments presenting century-old residents with commemorative sake cups and letters from the Prime Minister. Women account for roughly 88% of all centenarians, a gap that researchers attribute to differences in smoking rates, stress hormones, and immune function.\n\nThe Okinawan archipelago in Japan's south has drawn particular scientific attention as one of the world's five designated Blue Zones — regions where people live measurably longer than average in unusually good health. Researchers studying Okinawan centenarians have identified several recurring patterns: a traditional diet centered on purple sweet potato, bitter melon, tofu, seaweed, and modest portions of fish rather than red meat; a culture of ikigai — a sense of purpose and daily reason to get up in the morning that many Okinawans maintain well into their 90s; and the practice of moai — tight-knit social support groups of four or five friends who commit to supporting each other through life's hardships for decades.\n\nLongevity researchers caution that Japan's centenarian boom also reflects the success of its postwar healthcare system, which provides universal coverage with low out-of-pocket costs, and a culture of preventive medicine in which annual health screenings are routine from childhood. The social structure of traditional Japanese communities — where elders are venerated, remain engaged with family and community life, and rarely experience the isolation that shortens lives in many Western countries — also appears to be a significant protective factor. Japan's experience is increasingly studied by governments around the world grappling with aging populations who want to understand how to age well, not just longer.",
