    title: 'Bangladesh Floating Gardens Feed Thousands as Floods Rise',
    summary: 'Farmers in flood-prone Bangladesh have revived an ancient technique of growing vegetables on floating rafts of water hyacinth, adapting brilliantly to climate change and winning global recognition.',
    content: "In the waterlogged delta regions of southern Bangladesh — a low-lying country of 170 million people where climate-driven flooding is intensifying with every passing decade — farmers have perfected a 1,000-year-old agricultural technique that turns rising water from a catastrophe into an asset. Called baira or dhap, floating gardens are constructed by layering water hyacinth, aquatic weeds, and decomposing plant matter into buoyant platforms that can reach several metres in length and width. Farmers plant vegetables, spices, and seedlings directly into the soft compost of these platforms, which float on the surface of floodwaters and rise and fall naturally as the water level changes, never submerging the crops.\n\nThe technique requires no synthetic fertilizer — the decomposing plant matter beneath the growing layer provides a continuous supply of organic nutrients — and no pesticides, since the water surrounding the platforms acts as a natural barrier against many soil-borne insects. A single floating garden can produce multiple harvests per year, including leafy greens, gourds, bitter melon, chilli peppers, eggplant, and a range of herbs. In regions where conventional agriculture is impossible for four to six months per year due to flooding, floating gardens represent the difference between food security and dependence on emergency food aid.\n\nThe UN Food and Agriculture Organization has formally recognized Bangladesh's floating garden tradition as a Globally Important Agricultural Heritage System — a designation that identifies and protects traditional farming knowledge of outstanding universal value. Climate adaptation researchers from the Netherlands, the Philippines, and Bangladesh itself are now studying baira as a model for flood-resilient food production that could be adapted in other climate-vulnerable delta regions around the world. As sea level rise threatens to make large portions of coastal Asia more flood-prone, the knowledge encoded in this ancient technique has never been more urgent or more relevant.",
    sourceUrl: 'https://www.iied.org/moveable-feast-floating-gardens-bangladesh',
    sourceName: 'IIED',
    region: 'Asia',
    country: 'Bangladesh',
    category: 'Environment',
