    id: 'as-006',
    title: 'South Korea Rolls Out Universal Mental Health Services for All Citizens',
    summary: "South Korea launched a nationwide program providing free mental health screenings and counselling sessions to every citizen, tackling the country's historically high rates of work-related stress and depression.",
    content: "South Korea has long been one of the world's most high-pressure societies: students face grueling entrance exams that determine their life trajectories, workers log some of the longest hours among OECD nations, and a culture of hierarchical deference has historically made it difficult to acknowledge mental health struggles without fear of stigma or career consequences. The country's suicide rate has been among the highest in the developed world for over two decades, and depression and anxiety affect tens of millions of people who have largely suffered in silence. The government's nationwide mental health initiative represents a decisive break with this legacy — a formal acknowledgment that mental health is a public health crisis demanding a public health response.\n\nThe program offers every South Korean citizen free annual mental health screenings through primary care clinics and online platforms, free counselling sessions at community mental health centers (expanded from a previous network that was chronically underfunded and understaffed), and 24-hour crisis hotlines staffed by trained counsellors. Over 2 million people enrolled in the digital mental health check-in system in the first six months alone, suggesting that the stigma barrier — while not eliminated — is eroding rapidly, particularly among younger generations who grew up discussing mental health more openly online. The government is training 10,000 new community mental health workers over five years, partnering with tech companies to develop anonymous AI-assisted mood tracking tools, and embedding mental health education in school curricula from elementary through high school.\n\nCelebrity and public figure disclosures of personal mental health struggles have played a significant role in reducing stigma in South Korean society, with K-pop artists, actors, and athletes speaking openly about anxiety, depression, and burnout in ways that would have been career-ending just a decade ago. Mental health advocates say the government program and this cultural shift are reinforcing each other in a positive feedback loop — more openness about mental health makes it easier to seek help, which normalizes help-seeking further. Early data from pilot regions suggests measurable reductions in emergency psychiatric admissions and suicidal ideation in communities where the expanded services have been operating longest.",
