    title: 'Costa Rica Runs on 100% Renewable Energy for Over 300 Days a Year',
    summary: 'Costa Rica powered its entire electricity grid from wind, hydro, solar, and geothermal sources for more than 300 days in a single year — providing a blueprint for clean energy in tropical nations.',
    content: "Costa Rica — a tropical nation of just 5 million people — has powered its national electricity grid from renewable sources for over 300 days in a single year, achieving a 99% clean electricity figure that places it among the world's most advanced energy transitions. The country's mountainous geography is its greatest asset: dozens of hydroelectric dams harness the abundant rainfall that flows down from the Central Highlands, providing a highly reliable baseload of clean electricity that supplies roughly 70% of total generation in an average year. Wind farms along the Tilaran mountain range and the Pacific coast contribute another 15-20%, while geothermal plants tapping the volcanic Guanacaste region and a growing fleet of solar installations fill out the remainder.\n\nThe achievement is the product of decades of sustained public investment and political commitment. Costa Rica's publicly owned electricity utility, ICE, has operated since 1949 under a mandate that prioritizes universal access and energy independence over profit maximization. The country made a strategic decision in the 1970s to invest in hydropower rather than petroleum-based generation, a choice that insulated it from the oil price shocks that devastated other Central American economies and built the engineering expertise that now underlies its entire renewable sector.\n\nCostan Rica's clean electricity model has direct economic benefits that extend far beyond energy bills. The country has attracted significant foreign direct investment from technology companies and manufacturers specifically because of its green energy credentials and political stability — in a world where corporate sustainability commitments are increasingly binding, access to verifiably clean electricity is a competitive advantage. Eco-tourism, which draws visitors from around the world to experience Costa Rica's extraordinary biodiversity — the country contains 5% of all known species despite covering only 0.03% of Earth's land surface — is directly linked to the country's reputation as an environmental leader. The renewable electricity grid and the intact forests and coastlines that attract tourists are two expressions of the same underlying national commitment to ecological stewardship.",
