    id: 'la-007',
    title: "Chile's Atacama Solar Power Now Cheaper Than Coal Anywhere on Earth",
    summary: "Chile's Atacama desert — the sunniest place on Earth — is generating solar electricity at a world-record low cost, and the country is now building infrastructure to export that clean power across South America.",
    content: "Chile's Atacama desert receives more solar radiation per square metre than almost anywhere else on Earth — a consequence of its extreme altitude, near-zero cloud cover, and position at the edge of the subtropical high pressure belt that keeps the sky perpetually clear. This extraordinary solar resource, long known to geographers but until recently largely untapped, is now being converted into electricity at a price that has shattered all previous records for the cost of energy production. New utility-scale solar plants in the Atacama are delivering electricity at below US$20 per megawatt-hour — less than half the current global average for coal power, and lower than any fossil fuel source anywhere on Earth.\n\nThe consequence is a rapid and ongoing reshaping of Chile's electricity system. Solar generation now accounts for a growing share of daytime electricity supply, regularly pushing prices on the spot market to zero or even negative values during peak sunlight hours — a phenomenon that economists call 'solar saturation' and that was once considered an exotic future scenario. Chile has become a net electricity exporter, selling surplus solar power to neighboring Argentina through high-voltage interconnectors, and is developing new transmission infrastructure to reach Peru and Bolivia. The government is investing in grid-scale battery storage and pump hydro facilities to capture the solar surplus during the day and release it after dark, moving toward a system that is clean around the clock.\n\nThe long-term vision is green hydrogen. The combination of the world's cheapest solar electricity and vast uninhabited spaces in the Atacama makes Chile uniquely positioned to produce green hydrogen — made by using renewable electricity to split water molecules — at a cost that could undercut fossil fuel hydrogen anywhere in the world. Chile has signed preliminary agreements with Germany, Japan, and South Korea — three major industrial economies with large hydrogen demand and insufficient domestic renewable resources — to export green hydrogen and ammonia at scale within the decade. Energy economists say Chile's Atacama could become to the clean energy era what Saudi Arabia was to the petroleum era: the world's lowest-cost supplier of its most critical energy resource.",
    sourceUrl: 'https://www.zmescience.com/ecology/climate/cheapest-solar-power/',
    sourceName: 'ZME Science',
    region: 'Latin America',
    country: 'Chile',
    category: 'Science & Tech',
