    id: 'oc-002',
    title: "New Zealand's Māori Language Reaches One Million Speakers Milestone",
    summary: 'The Māori language (Te Reo Māori), once feared extinct, has reached one million speakers following generations of revival work through immersion schools, broadcasting, and official language status.',
    content: "Te Reo Māori — the language of New Zealand's indigenous Polynesian people, who arrived in the islands more than 700 years ago — has reached the milestone of one million speakers, including both fluent speakers and those with conversational competence. The achievement is the result of one of the most successful indigenous language revival efforts in modern history, reversing a trajectory that linguists a generation ago feared was terminal. In the 1970s, studies estimated that fewer than 70,000 people could speak Te Reo with any fluency, nearly all of them elderly, and linguists projected that the language could functionally die within a generation if nothing changed.\n\nThe transformation was driven by a combination of political advocacy, community-led innovation, and sustained government investment. The kōhanga reo — 'language nest' — movement, founded by Māori elders in 1982, created immersion early childhood centers where children from non-speaking families learned Māori as their first language before encountering English. The movement demonstrated that language could be transmitted across a generation gap that had seemed unbridgeable, and inspired the kura kaupapa Māori primary school system that extended immersion education through the school years. A dedicated Māori television channel launched in 2004 provided something no revival effort can function without: a reason for young people to engage with the language in contexts that feel modern and culturally relevant.\n\nNew Zealand's government officially recognized Te Reo Māori as a co-official language alongside English, required its use in government services, integrated it into the national curriculum, and normalized its presence in public life through signage, place names, and the names of government departments and institutions. Perhaps most importantly, the cultural prestige of Māori identity — expressed through haka, whakapapa (genealogy), and the language itself — has grown dramatically in New Zealand society, making fluency in Te Reo an asset rather than a marker of backwardness in the eyes of young New Zealanders of all backgrounds.",
